author: @bruinedrol1
text: Hi Krish Naik, If I'm not mistaking there is a slight error in your explanation at around 8:53 you are talking about that a single decision tree has low bias and a high variance but I think this is incorrect. Actually, a single decision tree (simple model) has high bias and low variance. The more complex your model gets the lower you bias and the higher your variance.    Quote from an article at Medium: "What is bias? Bias is the difference between the average prediction of our model and the correct value which we are trying to predict. Model with high bias pays very little attention to the training data and oversimplifies the model. It always leads to high error on training and test data.''   Source: https://towardsdatascience.com/understanding-the-bias-variance-tradeoff-165e6942b229 Hope this helps people that are a bit confused!
